theorem Topology.frontier_frontier_subset_frontier {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X]
    {A : Set X} :
    frontier (frontier (A : Set X)) ⊆ frontier A := by
  intro x hx
  -- Decompose the membership in the frontier of the frontier.
  have hx_cl_frontier : x ∈ closure (frontier (A : Set X)) := hx.1
  -- `frontier A ⊆ closure A`, hence their closures relate likewise.
  have h_closure_subset : closure (frontier (A : Set X)) ⊆ closure (A : Set X) := by
    have h_sub : frontier (A : Set X) ⊆ closure (A : Set X) := by
      intro y hy
      exact hy.1
    exact closure_mono h_sub
  -- Therefore `x ∈ closure A`.
  have hx_clA : x ∈ closure (A : Set X) := h_closure_subset hx_cl_frontier
  -- Show that `x ∉ interior A`.
  have hx_not_intA : x ∉ interior (A : Set X) := by
    intro hx_intA
    -- Any neighbourhood of `x` meets `frontier A`; take `interior A`.
    have h_nonempty :
        ((interior (A : Set X)) ∩ frontier (A : Set X)).Nonempty := by
      have h := (mem_closure_iff).1 hx_cl_frontier
      exact h _ isOpen_interior hx_intA
    rcases h_nonempty with ⟨y, ⟨hy_intA, hy_frontier⟩⟩
    -- But points of `frontier A` are not in `interior A`, contradiction.
    exact (hy_frontier.2) hy_intA
  -- Assemble the two facts to obtain the desired membership in `frontier A`.
  exact ⟨hx_clA, hx_not_intA⟩

theorem Topology.closure_eq_interior_union_frontier
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    closure (A : Set X) = interior A ∪ frontier A := by
  ext x
  constructor
  · intro hx_cl
    by_cases hx_int : x ∈ interior A
    · exact Or.inl hx_int
    · exact Or.inr ⟨hx_cl, hx_int⟩
  · intro hx
    cases hx with
    | inl hx_int =>
        exact interior_subset hx_int
    | inr hx_frontier =>
        exact hx_frontier.1
